\section{Limitations and Future Work}
%═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Current Limitations}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{UK$\times$UK Not Solved:} ZANS does not contract the structural noise from ciphertext-ciphertext multiplication. The $33$ bits/op cost remains unchanged. Our Fibonacci method requires the multiplier to be known in plaintext to the server. For applications requiring both operands encrypted, alternative approaches (bootstrapping, multi-party computation) remain necessary.
    
    \item \textbf{Speed Overhead:} The Fibonacci method is $17.7\times$ slower than native \texttt{multiply\_plain} in our unoptimized, single-threaded WSL2 implementation. Production optimization can reduce this to an estimated $2$--$3\times$.
    
    \item \textbf{Empirical Foundation:} The ZANS contraction mechanism lacks a formal mathematical proof. The connection to $\phi^{-1}$ is empirical and requires theoretical grounding from RLWE noise evolution first principles.
    
    \item \textbf{Reproduction Required:} All results are from a single implementation (Microsoft SEAL 4.3). Independent reproduction in OpenFHE \cite{openfhe2024}, Lattigo, HElib, or other libraries is essential for scientific validation.
    
    \item \textbf{Plaintext Modulus Constraint:} The $20$-bit plaintext modulus restricts multiplication results to $< 2^{20} \approx 10^6$. Larger moduli are needed for practical applications, at the cost of reduced initial noise budget.
    
    \item \textbf{Security Implications:} While ZANS does not modify the underlying RLWE security assumptions (it uses only standard BFV operations), the noise contraction behavior warrants careful cryptanalytic scrutiny to ensure no information leakage through noise patterns.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Future Work}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Mathematical Proof:} Derive the ZANS contraction coefficient $k = \phi^{-1}$ from first principles of RLWE noise evolution. A formal proof would elevate this from empirical observation to established theory.
    
    \item \textbf{UK$\times$UK via $\phi$-Spectral Decomposition:} The discovery that UK$\times$UK noise follows a $\phi$-harmonic structure (Section 7.3) suggests the possibility of spectral noise cancellation using $\phi$-weighted correction terms. This could potentially extend ZANS benefits to ciphertext-ciphertext multiplication.
    
    \item \textbf{Multiplicative ZANS (ZANS-M):} Investigate whether $\ct \times \Enc(1)$ or $\phi$-weighted multiplicative anchors ($\ct \times \Enc(\phi)$, $\ct \times \Enc(\phi^{-1})$) can provide analogous contraction for multiplicative noise. Preliminary results were negative, but deeper investigation is warranted.
    
    \item \textbf{Hardware Acceleration:} Implement ZANS and Fibonacci multiplication with AVX2/AVX-512 SIMD, NTT polynomial optimization, and GPU acceleration (CUDA/OpenCL). Estimated speedup: $100$--$1{,}000\times$.
    
    \item \textbf{Large-Scale Riemann Validation:} Extend the $\phi$-harmonic gap ratio analysis to $10^6$ zeta zeros to achieve $5\sigma$ statistical significance, strengthening the $\phi$-Unity Principle.
    
    \item \textbf{Application-Specific Optimization:} Develop domain-specific ZANS configurations for:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Privacy-preserving neural network inference (matrix-vector products with known weights)
        \item Encrypted polynomial evaluation (Horner's method with ZANS)
        \item Secure aggregation (Federated learning with thousands of participants)
        \item Encrypted database queries (range queries, aggregations)
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item \textbf{Formal Security Analysis:} Comprehensive IND-CPA security proof in the ZANS-augmented model, analysis of potential side-channel leakage through noise timing, and investigation of whether the Banach fixed point introduces any distinguishing advantage.
\end{enumerate}

