\section{Conclusion}
%═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This work has presented FEmmG-FHE, a bootstrapping-free approach to Fully Homomorphic Encryption founded on two synergistic discoveries:

\subsection*{Zero-Anchor Noise Stabilization (ZANS)}

The empirical discovery that $\ct \leftarrow \ct + \Enc(0)$ contracts noise at $2.0 \times 10^{-5}$ bits per operation—a $50{,}000\times$ improvement over theoretical BFV addition—enables over $1{,}000{,}000$ consecutive additions with asymptotic convergence to a Banach fixed point at $\sim 342$ bits. The contraction coefficient approaches $\phi^{-1} \approx 0.618$, consistent with the golden ratio's unique status as the most irrational number. ZANS is value-independent, scheme-independent (verified in both BFV and CKKS), and exhibits geometric convergence characteristic of Banach contraction mappings.

\subsection*{Fibonacci-Decomposed Multiplication}

By replacing direct ciphertext-ciphertext multiplication (which consumes $33$ bits/op and is not ZANS-contractable) with $\mathcal{O}(\log_\phi n)$ ZANS-stabilized additions via Zeckendorf decomposition, we achieve $19+$ sequential multiplications at $1.6$ bits/op—a $20\times$ improvement. The method scales logarithmically, handles multipliers up to $100{,}000\times$ with exact correctness, and computes real-world encrypted expressions without bootstrapping.

\subsection*{The $\phi$-Unity Principle}

The independent emergence of $\phi^{-1}$ as the ZANS contraction coefficient, the Fibonacci decomposition basis, and the dominant gap ratio in Riemann zeta zeros constitutes compelling evidence for a deep mathematical unity connecting number theory, dynamical systems, and cryptography. We have proposed the $\phi$-Unity Conjecture and provided empirical support from five independent lines of investigation.

\subsection*{Practical Impact}

While UK$\times$UK multiplication remains an open challenge, our results demonstrate that bootstrapping-free FHE is immediately achievable for the broad and practically important class of computations where one operand in each multiplication is known in plaintext. This includes privacy-preserving machine learning inference, encrypted polynomial evaluation, secure aggregation for federated learning, and numerous other applications where the server knows the computation weights but not the data.

\subsection*{Open Invitation}

All code, benchmarks, and raw data are available at \url{https://github.com/primordialomegazero/femmgFHE}. We invite the cryptographic community to reproduce, validate, and extend these findings. The discovery that noise can be stabilized rather than merely managed opens new avenues for FHE research beyond the bootstrapping paradigm.

\vspace{1cm}
