\section*{Appendix C: Response to Reviewer Comments}
\addcontentsline{toc}{section}{Appendix C: Response to Reviewer Comments}

We thank the reviewer for their thorough and constructive analysis of FEmmG-FHE. We address each concern below.

\subsection*{C.1 On the ZANS Contraction Mechanism}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{Why does adding Enc(0) contract noise? What is the metric space and distance function?}

This is the central theoretical gap in our work, and we are transparent about its empirical—not theoretical—foundation. Standard RLWE noise theory predicts additive growth: $\|e_{\text{total}}\| \approx \|e_{\text{ct}}\| + \|e_{\text{new}}\|$. Our empirical observation contradicts this prediction, and we offer the following hypothesis for formal investigation.

\textbf{Hypothesized Mechanism (Speculative):}

The noise in a BFV ciphertext is a polynomial $e(x) \in R_q = \mathbb{Z}_q[x]/(x^N + 1)$ with $N = 16{,}384$ coefficients. The SEAL function \texttt{invariant\_noise\_budget()} measures:
\begin{equation}
\text{noise\_budget}(\ct) = \log_2\left(\frac{q}{2\|e\|_\infty}\right)
\end{equation}
where $\|e\|_\infty = \max_i |e_i|$ is the worst-case coefficient bound (the $\ell_\infty$ norm).

We hypothesize that ZANS operates through a \textbf{norm conversion} mechanism:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item $\Enc(0)$ carries fresh noise $e_{\text{new}}$ with a random sign pattern, uniformly distributed over $\{-1, 0, 1\}^N$ (for ternary secret distribution).
    \item The existing ciphertext noise $e_{\text{ct}}$ has a structured sign pattern reflecting its operational history (additions, multiplications).
    \item In high-dimensional spaces ($N = 16{,}384$), random vectors are approximately orthogonal to structured vectors with high probability.
    \item Adding a near-orthogonal random vector to a structured vector \textbf{redistributes energy}: the $\ell_\infty$ norm (maximum coefficient) decreases while the $\ell_2$ norm (total energy $\sum e_i^2$) may slightly increase.
    \item The \texttt{invariant\_noise\_budget()} metric captures only the $\ell_\infty$ reduction, not the $\ell_2$ increase.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Why $\phi^{-1} \approx 0.618$?} We do not have a proof. The empirical convergence rate approaches $\phi^{-1}$ near the fixed point. This may relate to the spectral geometry of the cyclotomic ring $R_q$, where the eigenvalues of the discrete Fourier transform matrix for $N$ a power of 2 involve roots of unity whose ratios include $\phi$ for certain dimensions. Alternatively, $\phi^{-1}$ as the ``most irrational'' number (continued fraction $[0; 1, 1, 1, \ldots]$) provides optimal mixing in quasi-periodic systems, potentially maximizing the destructive interference rate.

\textbf{The Banach Framework:} The proposed metric space is $(R_q, \|\cdot\|_\infty)$ restricted to the noise component. The operator $T(\ct) = \ct + \Enc(0)$ would be a contraction if:
\begin{equation}
\|e_{\text{ct}} + e_{\text{new}}\|_\infty \leq k \cdot \|e_{\text{ct}}\|_\infty, \quad k \in [0, 1)
\end{equation}

This inequality does \textbf{not} hold for arbitrary $e_{\text{ct}}$ and $e_{\text{new}}$—it requires the geometric relationship described above. Formal proof remains open.

\textbf{Verification Suggestion:} Direct measurement of both $\ell_\infty$ and $\ell_2$ noise norms before and after ZANS would confirm or refute the norm conversion hypothesis. SEAL does not expose $\ell_2$ noise measurement, requiring modification of the library.

\subsection*{C.2 On UK$\times$UK Multiplication}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{Is there any scenario where ZANS could contract UK$\times$UK noise?}

After extensive experimentation (Section 5.4, Table 10), we conclude that UK$\times$UK multiplication noise is \textbf{not ZANS-contractable} under any tested variant. We evaluated:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Standard ZANS (10,000 operations on post-UK$\times$UK ciphertext): 0 bits contraction
    \item ZANS-M (multiply by $\Enc(1)$): $-33$ bits (additional noise)
    \item ModSwitch + ZANS: $-41$ bits (worse than baseline due to modulus level reduction)
    \item $\phi$-spectral kernel ZANS: 0 bits
    \item Fibonacci-pattern ZANS: 0 bits
    \item Riemann zeta gap schedule ZANS: 0 bits
    \item Hybrid ZANS + ZANS-M combinations: catastrophic noise growth
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Why UK$\times$UK noise is structural:} The tensor product in ciphertext multiplication fundamentally restructures the polynomial coefficients. The resulting noise is algebraically embedded through the relinearization process and cannot be addressed by additive operations. This is analogous to attempting to reduce JPEG compression artifacts by adding Gaussian noise—the artifacts are structural, not thermal.

\textbf{Limitation:} Our Fibonacci multiplication method requires the multiplier to be known in plaintext. For applications with both operands encrypted, bootstrapping or multi-party computation techniques remain necessary. However, the class of computations with known plaintext multipliers is substantial and practically important:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Neural network inference (weights are server-known)
    \item Polynomial evaluation (coefficients are server-known)
    \item Encrypted database queries (query parameters are server-known)
    \item Secure aggregation with known weights
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{C.3 On the $\phi$-Riemann Connection}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{Can you provide the mathematical mechanism connecting RLWE noise to Riemann zeta zeros?}

\textbf{Honest answer: No.} This connection is currently \textbf{purely empirical} and we present it as an observation, not a theorem. The $\phi$-Unity Principle is explicitly labeled as a \textbf{conjecture} (Conjecture 7.1).

We acknowledge the reviewer's valid criticisms:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Sample size:} Only 200 zeta zeros analyzed. This is insufficient for definitive statistical claims. We are pursuing access to $10^6$-zero datasets.
    \item \textbf{Statistical significance:} $z > 1.8\sigma$ exceeds the 96th percentile but falls well short of the $5\sigma$ ($p < 3 \times 10^{-7}$) standard for discovery claims in physics.
    \item \textbf{Multiple comparisons:} Testing multiple $\phi$-related values ($\phi/2$, $\phi^{-1}$, $\phi$, $\phi^{-2}$) increases the false discovery rate. A Bonferroni correction would raise the significance threshold.
    \item \textbf{No theoretical mechanism:} We do not claim a causal or mechanistic link between RLWE noise dynamics and zeta zero statistics.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Why we included it anyway:} The convergence of $\phi$ in three independent contexts—cryptographic noise contraction, algorithmic decomposition, and prime number spectral organization—is suggestive enough to warrant mention and invite further investigation. We believe the scientific community benefits from sharing such observations, even when the underlying mechanism is unknown.

\subsection*{C.4 On Security Implications}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{Does ZANS create a side-channel? What prevents an adversary from using ZANS to ``clean'' ciphertexts?}

\textbf{Side-Channel Analysis (Preliminary):}

\textit{Potential concern:} An adversary observing the ZANS contraction \textit{rate} might infer operational history (e.g., ``this ciphertext underwent 5 multiplications before ZANS'').

\textit{Mitigating factors:}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Fixed schedule:} ZANS should be applied deterministically (e.g., after every addition) rather than adaptively. This eliminates timing-based leakage.
    \item \textbf{Universal convergence:} All ciphertexts converge to the same fixed point ($N^* \approx 341.5$) at the same asymptotic rate ($\phi^{-1}$), regardless of their operational history. After sufficient ZANS, ciphertexts with different histories become statistically indistinguishable.
    \item \textbf{Operation indistinguishability:} The adversary cannot distinguish $\ct + \Enc(0)$ from $\ct + \Enc(m)$ without the secret key. ZANS operations are cryptographically identical to standard homomorphic additions.
    \item \textbf{Noise budget is already public:} In standard FHE, the noise budget is inferable from ciphertext size/modulus level. ZANS does not introduce new observables.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Can adversaries ``clean'' ciphertexts?} Yes—and this is \textbf{not a vulnerability}. ZANS is a public algorithm; any party can apply it to any ciphertext. The result is a ciphertext with noise contracted toward the fixed point but still encrypted under the original key. Decryption remains impossible without the secret key because:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item IND-CPA security of BFV relies on the RLWE assumption, which is independent of noise budget magnitude (above the correctness threshold).
    \item A ciphertext at the noise floor (341 bits) is still computationally indistinguishable from a fresh encryption under RLWE.
    \item Noise contraction does not leak plaintext bits—it only affects the noise polynomial.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Formal Security:} We have not provided an IND-CPA security proof in the ZANS-augmented model. This is important future work. Since ZANS uses only standard BFV operations (addition), we do not anticipate new cryptographic assumptions, but the modified noise distribution warrants formal analysis.

\subsection*{C.5 On Reproduction}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{What steps have been taken to ensure reproducibility?}

\textbf{Current state:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Complete source code:} All benchmarks are available at \url{https://github.com/primordialomegazero/femmgFHE} with compilation instructions.
    \item \textbf{CKKS cross-validation:} Successfully reproduced ZANS in CKKS (Section 3.6), confirming scheme independence within Microsoft SEAL.
    \item \textbf{Parameter documentation:} All parameters ($N=16384$, $q=\texttt{CoeffModulus::BFVDefault}$, $t=20$-bit batching) are explicitly stated.
    \item \textbf{Raw output:} Complete terminal logs are included in Appendix B.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Remaining validation needed:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Cross-library:} OpenFHE, Lattigo, HElib implementations
    \item \textbf{Cross-parameter:} $N=2048, 4096, 8192, 32768$ with appropriate $q, t$
    \item \textbf{Cross-platform:} Native Linux (non-WSL), macOS, Windows
    \item \textbf{Cross-compiler:} Clang, MSVC
\end{itemize}

We invite the community to attempt reproduction. The experiments are designed to be runnable on consumer hardware (the 1M ZANS test completes in $\sim$10 minutes on a single core).

\subsection*{C.6 On Practical Deployment}

\textbf{Reviewer Question:} \textit{What would be required to deploy this in production?}

\textbf{Engineering requirements:}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Performance optimization:} SIMD vectorization (AVX2/AVX-512) for polynomial addition, estimated $10$--$50\times$ speedup.
    \item \textbf{Fibonacci basis caching:} Pre-compute and cache Fibonacci terms for frequently-used base values. A 30-term cache supports multipliers up to $\sim 1.3 \times 10^6$.
    \item \textbf{Modulus level management:} Integrate with existing modulus switching pipelines. ZANS contraction rate is consistent across levels.
    \item \textbf{Thread safety:} ZANS operations on different ciphertexts are independent and parallelizable.
    \item \textbf{Security audit:} Formal IND-CPA proof, side-channel analysis, noise distribution characterization.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Applicability criteria:} ZANS/Fibonacci FHE is applicable when:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item At least one operand in each multiplication is known in plaintext to the server
    \item The computation is addition-heavy (e.g., aggregation, dot products)
    \item Bootstrapping latency is unacceptable (real-time applications)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{When bootstrapping is still required:}
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item Both operands encrypted (true UK$\times$UK multiplication)
    \item Very deep multiplication chains ($> 200$ sequential multiplications)
    \item Applications requiring exact FHE with full ciphertext-ciphertext operations
\end{itemize}

